        <div class="modal-body">
          <p>Purandara Dasa (ಪುರಂದರ ದಾಸ) was a Haridasa, a great devotee of Lord Krishna. He was a singer and composer of many songs on Madhwa philosophy. Purandara Dasa was pioneers of Dasa Sahithya, which is a Bhakti movement and propagated Hari Sarvottama and Vayu Jeevottamatva though his 475,000 keerthanas (songs). He wrote all his compositions with Ankita "Purandara Vittala". He is as an avatara (incarnation) of the great sage Narada.
            His Guru, Sri Vyasatirtha himself glorified Purandara Dasa in a song thus: Dāsarendare purandara dāsarayya (ದಾಸರೆಂದರೆ ಪುರಂದರ ದಾಸರಯ್ಯ). </p>
            <p>Brief Story:
                Before becoming Haridasa, Purandara Dasa was a wealthy diamond merchant. His name was Srinivasa Nayaka and everyone used to call him Navakoti Narayana as he was very rich worth of ninety millions. His parents are Varadappa Nayaka and Leelavathi. He was born around year 1484  in Kshemapura, near Tirthahalli, Shivamogga district, Karnataka state from Karnataka. He received good education and became proficient in caranatic music, Kannada and Sanskrit languages. 
                One day Lord Krishna approached Srinivasa in the guise of a poor man to request for money to perform upanayanam (sacred thread ceremony) to his son. For which, Srinivasa mocked and rejected him without offering any money. Therefor to bring change in him, Lord approached Srinivasa's wife, Saraswathi who is a pious and spiritual person,she gave her precious nose rings.
                Lord Krishna then met Srinivasa to exchange the nose ring with money. But the shrewd Srinivasa immediately identified the nose ring as his wife's and hurried home anxiously to ascertain the truth of the matter, he demanded his wife to show him the nose ring immediately. Realizing that Srinivasa got to know about her secret donation, the wife decided to end her life with poison. She prayed Lord before drinking poison, she was shocked to see a nose ring inside the poison cup. With blissful happiness she elucidated the entire episode to her husband, who was bewildered. 
                The entire episode brought change in Srinivasa Nayaka, who gave away all his material riches to become a Haridasa, a devotional singer. He became disciple of Madhwa Saint Shri Vyasatirtha. He is contemporary of Kanakadasaru and has inspired many people like Vijaya dasaru, Gopala Dasaru and so on. He died in 1564 at the age of 80.</p>
